{
  "title": "VimFu — Ctrl-N / Ctrl-P",
  "description": "Ctrl-N and Ctrl-P move down and up in normal mode, but the real reason to know them is the N=Next / P=Previous mnemonic carries into insert-mode autocomplete and command-line history.",
  "speed": 0.55,
  "rows": 20,
  "cols": 40,
  "humanize": 0.7,
  "seed": 380,
  "ttsVoice": "echo",
  "playlist": "VimFu",
  "tags": [
    "vim",
    "neovim",
    "nvim",
    "vimfu",
    "tutorial",
    "terminal",
    "editor",
    "coding",
    "programming",
    "keyboard"
  ],
  "setup": [
    {
      "comment": "Set TERM for proper color support in Neovim"
    },
    {
      "line": "export TERM=xterm-256color"
    },
    {
      "comment": "Prepare workspace"
    },
    {
      "line": "mkdir -p ~/vimfu && cd ~/vimfu"
    },
    {
      "line": "rm -f crew.py .crew.py.swp .crew.py.swo"
    },
    {
      "line": "rm -f ~/.local/state/nvim/swap/*crew.py*"
    },
    {
      "comment": "Create demo file"
    },
    {
      "writeFile": "crew.py",
      "content": "pilot = \"Kai\"\ngunner = \"Rex\"\nmedic = \"Nova\"\nengineer = \"Bolt\"\ncaptain = \"Vex\""
    },
    {
      "line": "clear"
    },
    {
      "comment": "Launch nvim"
    },
    {
      "line": "nvim crew.py"
    },
    {
      "waitForScreen": "All",
      "timeout": 30.0
    },
    {
      "ifScreen": "swap file",
      "thenKeys": "d"
    }
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "comment": "--- Title card ---"
    },
    {
      "overlay": "VimFu",
      "caption": "Ctrl-N / Ctrl-P",
      "duration": 2.0
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.7
    },
    {
      "comment": "--- Intro ---"
    },
    {
      "say": "Control N moves down one line, just like J. Control P moves up one line, just like K."
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "comment": "--- Demo 1: Ctrl-N down ---"
    },
    {
      "say": "We're on line one, pilot. Control N.",
      "wait": false
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "ctrl": "n",
      "overlay": "down"
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.5
    },
    {
      "ctrl": "n",
      "overlay": "down"
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.5
    },
    {
      "say": "Down two lines. Cursor is on medic now. Same as pressing J twice."
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "comment": "--- Demo 2: Ctrl-P up ---"
    },
    {
      "say": "Control P goes back up.",
      "wait": false
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "ctrl": "p",
      "overlay": "up"
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.5
    },
    {
      "say": "Up one line to gunner. Just like K."
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "comment": "--- Demo 3: with count ---"
    },
    {
      "say": "They take counts too. Three control N.",
      "wait": false
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "keys": "3",
      "overlay": "count 3"
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "ctrl": "n",
      "overlay": "down"
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.6
    },
    {
      "say": "Down three lines to captain. N for next line, P for previous line."
    },
    {
      "wait": 0.3
    },
    {
      "comment": "--- Wrap up ---"
    },
    {
      "say": "So why not just use J and K? Because N means next and P means previous, and that same mnemonic shows up everywhere in Vim. In insert mode, control N and control P cycle through autocomplete suggestions. On the command line, they navigate your command history. J and K don't work in those contexts. Learn the N P pattern now, and it'll pay off later."
    },
    {
      "wait": 1.5
    }
  ],
  "teardown": [
    {
      "comment": "Quit nvim without saving"
    },
    "escape",
    {
      "type": ":q!"
    },
    "enter",
    {
      "comment": "Clean up"
    },
    {
      "line": "rm -f crew.py"
    }
  ],
